Lizeka Tandwa, News24FILE: South African interior minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma speaks during a press conference as head of the African Union (AU) Commission. (Simon Maina, AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - The next president of the ANC must be a woman, The party's women's league declared on Sunday.&nbsp;"We are not backing down on our mandate that the next president of the ANC must be a woman," it said in a statement.&nbsp;The ANCWL held its national executive committee meeting this weekend. &nbsp;It proposed that the top six of the ANC must have 50/50 representation.&nbsp;"Women must enforce the 50/50 representation policy of the ANC in all our structures and... towards the policy conference we want to propose that the top six of the ANC must have 50/50 representation."The league also plans to lobby for the top six of the ANC to be a recognised structure.It noted with concern that during the pre-election list process, many women were nominated and supported by communities but were removed.&nbsp;"Some could not come out because they feared for their lives. We experienced the most brutal and most cruel and merciless killings of women comrades and we cannot allow this to continue," it said.&nbsp;Earlier this year, News24 reported that African Union (AU) Commission chairperson Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma had given the strongest indication yet that she would be in the running for ANC president come 2017.News24 asked her after the closing of the AU heads of state summit whether her staying for another nine months at the helm of the continental body would affect her campaign in the ANC. She indicated that she would be free to take up the position if required."The [ANC] conference is 2017 December," she said.She added, laughing, that her current position "has got nothing to do with the ANC. The ANC has its own processes".A fresh round of AU elections is set to take place in January, followed by a three-month handover, after which Dlamini-Zuma would return home.Dlamini-Zuma is the first female AU chairperson, and some in the ANC, are campaigning for her to become the party and the country's first female president. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.